            <dc:description xml:lang="slv">Ivan Siter, rojen leta 1924, prisilno mobiliziran v Wehrmacht in odposlan v severno Francijo. Tik pred zavezniško invazijo v Normandiji (6. junij 1944) si je vzel dopust in se napotil v okupirano Slovenijo. Po nenadnem nemškem ukazu o prekinitvi trajanja vseh dopustov so njegov vlak v Avstriji preusmerili za vzhodno fronto. Doma je že imel zvezo za vstop v Savski odred. Sovjeti so ga ujeli v Pripjatskem močvirju in poslali v ujetništvo v bližino reke Kame pod vznožje Urala. Ob koncu leta 1946 se je v zelo slabotnem stanju vrnil domov.</dc:description>
            <dc:description xml:lang="eng">Ivan Siter, born in 1924, forced to conscript into the Wehrmacht and sent to northern France. Just before the Allies invaded Normandy (6 June 1944) he went on leave and headed for the occupied Slovenia. After a sudden German order to cancel all leaves, his train was redirected in Austria to the Eastern Front. Back home, he had connections that would have enabled him to join the partisan Sava Detachment. He was captured by the Soviets in the Pinsk Marshes and sent to a prison near the Kama River at the foot of the Ural Mountains. He returned home in late 1946, but very feeble.</dc:description>
            <dcterms:provenance>Janez Siter</dcterms:provenance>
